Compute architecture
A two-tier compute split works best. Use a Raspberry Pi 5 (or Jetson Orin Nano if you want on-device vision/LLM inference) as the "brain" running the face, voice, planning, and high-level logic. Pair it with an ESP32 or Teensy 4.x as the real-time "spinal cord" handling motor PWM, encoder reads, IMU fusion, and emergency stops at 100–1000 Hz. The two talk over USB-serial or UART. This split is standard in serious hobby and research robots because Linux is bad at hard real-time control and microcontrollers are bad at heavy compute.
Locomotion
Three reasonable options, in increasing complexity:
Differential drive — two driven wheels plus a caster — is the easiest to control, cheapest, and what I'd recommend unless you have a reason to upgrade. Use two DC gearmotors (12 V, ~200 RPM, with quadrature encoders, e.g. Pololu 37D series) and cut wheel arches into the bottom face so wheels sit partially inside the box.
Mecanum/omni wheels (4 driven wheels) let the robot strafe sideways and rotate in place independently — great for navigating tight spaces — but kinematics are more involved and you need 4 motor channels.
Tracks are overkill indoors but useful on carpet/uneven floors.
For the motor driver, a Cytron MDD10A or DRV8871 module per channel handles 12 V gearmotors comfortably. Avoid L298N — it's lossy and dated.
Display / face
You have two main paths. A single rectangular touchscreen (7" or 5" HDMI/DSI, e.g. the official Pi 7" display) on one face is simplest — animate the face in Pygame, Qt/QML, or as a fullscreen web app (HTML/CSS/SVG is surprisingly nice for expressive faces because animation tooling is mature). Alternatively, two small round IPS displays (1.28" or 2.1", GC9A01-based) as separate "eyes" gives a Vector/Cozmo-style look with more character but more complexity.
Pick the display first — its mounting cutout drives the front-panel design.
Sensors
Minimum viable set: IMU (BNO055 gives you fused orientation out of the box), wheel encoders (already on the motors), and 3–5 forward-facing ToF distance sensors (VL53L1X) for obstacle avoidance. Add a USB or CSI camera for vision. If you want real navigation/SLAM, an RPLidar A1 (~$100) on top of the cube enables ROS 2 Nav2 to do mapping and autonomous path planning out of the box. A microphone (USB conference mic or ReSpeaker 2-Mic HAT) and a small amplified speaker (e.g. Adafruit MAX98357 I2S amp + 3 W driver) cover voice I/O.
Power
A 3S or 4S Li-ion pack (3× or 4× 18650, ~10–12 Ah) gives you several hours of runtime and fits easily. Use a proper BMS with overcurrent/overdischarge protection. Step down to 5 V (5 A buck converter) for the Pi and 3.3 V for sensors; feed motors directly from the pack through the driver. Add an XT60 charging port, a master switch, and a fuse on the battery output. A coulomb counter (INA219/INA226) lets the robot report its own battery state.
Software stack
ROS 2 (Humble or Jazzy on Ubuntu 24.04) is the right choice if you want navigation, sensor fusion, and modular nodes — it pays off fast even though the learning curve is real. For the face and conversational layer, a Python process running Pygame or a Chromium kiosk publishes/subscribes to ROS topics ("emotion", "speech_state", "battery") so the face reacts to robot state. For voice, Whisper.cpp (small model) handles speech-to-text locally; Piper does fast neural TTS; an LLM call (local via llama.cpp or remote API) handles dialogue. The ESP32 runs a small firmware exposing /cmd_vel → motor commands and publishing /odom and /imu via micro-ROS or a simple serial protocol.
