Build it in this sequence — each layer gets you a working milestone before you commit to the next:

Chassis + drivetrain only. Laser-cut acrylic or 3D-printed PETG frame, motors, wheels, battery, ESP32, driver. Goal: it drives forward/back/turns from serial commands.
Add the Pi and the link. Get ROS 2 on the Pi, micro-ROS or a serial protocol on the ESP32, publish /odom and accept /cmd_vel. Drive it with teleop_twist_keyboard.
Add the face. Mount the screen, get an animated face running fullscreen on Pi boot. Wire it to a ROS topic so the face reflects state (idle/listening/moving).
Add sensing. ToF ring + IMU + camera. Test obstacle avoidance as a behavior.
Add voice and intelligence. STT → intent/LLM → TTS pipeline. Connect intents to robot behaviors.
Add LiDAR + Nav2 if you want autonomous navigation. This is the biggest single jump in capability.

A few decisions worth making early
A few things to nail down early because they cascade through the whole design: indoor-only vs ability to handle thresholds and rugs (changes wheel diameter and motor torque), how much autonomy you want (teleoperation needs almost nothing; SLAM and autonomous navigation pushes you toward Jetson + LiDAR), how the robot charges (manual plug is fine for a prototype; a contact-pad dock is a serious mechanical project), and whether the face needs to look "alive" when idle (driving the look-and-feel of the animation more than the hardware).
