Combine those into three realistic scenarios:

Idle / "alive but parked" (face animated, listening, no motion): ~10–12 W
Active conversation + light driving: ~25–30 W
Driving + vision + speaking simultaneously: ~40–50 W
Worst-case spike (both motors near stall): well over 100 W, brief

Sustained average for a chatty mobile robot lands around 18–22 W. Size the battery for that average; size the wiring and fuses for the stall case.
Battery sizing
A 4S Li-ion pack (14.4 V nominal, 16.8 V full) is the sweet spot — drives the 12 V motors directly through a buck regulator and steps down cleanly to 5 V for the Pi. Concrete option:

4S2P 18650 with 3000 mAh cells: ~14.4 V × 6 Ah = 86 Wh
Mixed-use runtime: ~4 hours
Active driving: ~2.5 hours
Pack dimensions: roughly 75 × 40 × 70 mm
Weight: ~380 g
Add a 4S BMS board (~70 × 25 mm), an XT60 charging connector, and a master switch

If you want more endurance, 4S3P (12 cells, ~130 Wh) gives ~6 hours mixed at ~95 × 60 × 70 mm and ~570 g — still tiny relative to the cube. A 4S LiPo pouch (5000–8000 mAh) is lighter for the same energy but needs more careful charging and impact protection.
For charging, a 16.8 V 2 A smart charger plugged into the XT60 refills 4S2P in about 3 hours. The Pi gets its own 5 V via a 5 A buck (Pololu D24V50F5 or similar); sensors run off a small 3.3 V LDO.
Physical size — what fits and what doesn't
The 25 cm cube gives you ~15.6 liters of internal volume. Subtracting walls, brackets, and the screen recess, you have roughly 12 liters usable. Approximate footprints of the major occupants:

Two 37 mm gearmotors with gearboxes and 100 mm wheels: ~0.6 L combined (plus they protrude through the floor)
Battery (4S2P): ~0.22 L
Raspberry Pi 5 with cooler: ~0.1 L
7" display + driver board, mounted to the front face: ~0.15 L
Motor driver + DC-DC boards + ESP32: ~0.2 L
LiDAR on the top face: ~0.15 L
Speaker, mic array, cable runs, fasteners: ~0.5 L

That's about 2 liters of actual hardware in a 15-liter shell. Space is not your constraint — layout, weight distribution, and thermal management are. A few practical notes:

Put the battery low and centered for a low center of gravity. Wheelbase is roughly 18–20 cm, so a top-heavy load will tip on quick turns.
Estimated total weight: 2.5–3.0 kg. Motors sized at ~3 kg·cm continuous torque per wheel (e.g. Pololu 37D 50:1) handle that comfortably and give ~1 m/s top speed with 100 mm wheels.
Leave a vent slot on one face (or a quiet fan) for the Pi 5 — it throttles around 80 °C and a sealed cube hits that fast under load.
The LiDAR needs an unobstructed 360° horizontal sweep, which usually means mounting it on the top face with the rest of the cube ducking just below its scan plane.

If runtime matters more than mass, scale the pack up to 4S3P; if you'd rather a lighter robot for safer falls and easier handling, the 4S2P at ~3 kg is the better balance.
